514
00:38:16,076 --> 00:38:17,960
and I need a glass of
water, and then you can go.

515
00:38:21,665 --> 00:38:23,799
Oh, that's very pretty.

516
00:38:25,903 --> 00:38:27,570
Thank you.

517
00:38:36,330 --> 00:38:38,064
- When are you due?
- Early September.

518
00:38:38,098 --> 00:38:39,749
You and the first lady.

519
00:38:39,833 --> 00:38:42,385
Well, I think she looks a lot better.

520
00:38:42,469 --> 00:38:43,887
You could dress like that.

521
00:38:43,971 --> 00:38:45,838
Go to Lord & Taylor and ask
for my friend Bunny Appelle.

522
00:38:45,890 --> 00:38:47,974
- She'll take care of you.
- You really know everything Joan.

523
00:38:50,878 --> 00:38:53,930
Honey, would you talk to your husband?

524
00:38:54,214 --> 00:38:56,466
I don't know what I'm
going to do next year.

525
00:38:57,768 --> 00:39:00,019
He is going to be a tough act to follow.

526
00:39:00,070 --> 00:39:03,122
Those people in Texas will
be crawling all over you.

527
00:39:03,157 --> 00:39:05,858
If I ever need a pneumonectomy,
that's the man.

528
00:39:05,926 --> 00:39:08,011
Well, you heard me say it... 

529
00:39:08,095 --> 00:39:09,262
Great hands.

530
00:39:12,833 --> 00:39:15,835
Look, Greg, it's a
complicated operation.

531
00:39:15,869 --> 00:39:17,904
Oh, Christ, that's not what I meant.

532
00:39:17,938 --> 00:39:20,006
- It happens.
- What happened?

533
00:39:21,842 --> 00:39:24,711
I don't like to worry Joanie
about those kinds of things.

534
00:39:24,745 --> 00:39:27,497
Oh, come on. Everyone gets a bad
result every once in a while.

535
00:39:30,751 --> 00:39:32,985
You know what?
Enough shop talk.

536
00:39:33,020 --> 00:39:34,821
This is not civilian conversation.

537
00:39:36,957 --> 00:39:39,575
Do you want to play charades?

538
00:39:39,660 --> 00:39:42,261
- Come on. You're terrible.
- No, I'm not.

539
00:39:42,296 --> 00:39:46,098
Well, Joanie has many many talents.

540
00:39:46,150 --> 00:39:47,784
You should play for them.

541
00:39:47,851 --> 00:39:50,536
- No.
- Come on. I'll go get it.

542
00:39:53,874 --> 00:39:56,309
- You're all gonna love this.
- What do you play?

543
00:39:56,343 --> 00:39:58,111
I am out of practice.

544
00:39:58,145 --> 00:40:01,080
- Come on, Joanie.
- Wonderful!

545
00:40:01,115 --> 00:40:04,417
Come on, just sing a
little something.

546
00:40:08,655 --> 00:40:10,890
It'll be just like the olden days.

547
00:40:10,941 --> 00:40:12,759
We used to sit in
the parlor after supper.

548
00:40:12,793 --> 00:40:14,560
My mother would play
the piano while we read.

549
00:41:21,595 --> 00:41:23,396
Just let me have another
bite and then we can go.

550
00:41:31,288 --> 00:41:33,372
I guess we're the last ones to eat.

551
00:41:33,407 --> 00:41:35,374
That's what my mother always said.

552
00:41:35,425 --> 00:41:38,344
Family holds back. Oh!

553
00:41:40,347 --> 00:41:43,649
You shouldn't be filling your plate.
You're the hostess.

554
00:41:43,700 --> 00:41:45,785
- I'll get you some food.
- Come on. Come on.

555
00:41:45,819 --> 00:41:49,338
- You should sit down.
- Oh, okay.

556
00:41:49,423 --> 00:41:52,758
Oh my God! You're pregnant.

557
00:41:52,793 --> 00:41:55,361
- You're so beautiful.
- Thank you.

558
00:41:55,395 --> 00:41:57,230
Don't you just love looking at her?

559
00:41:57,264 --> 00:41:59,999
Aren't they a beautiful couple?

560
00:42:00,033 --> 00:42:02,919
I knew you two would get back together.

561
00:42:05,439 --> 00:42:07,940
I never had any doubt, no
matter what the problem was.

562
00:42:09,593 --> 00:42:11,010
I'll take care of her.

563
00:42:17,851 --> 00:42:20,152
You don't like me.

564
00:42:20,187 --> 00:42:23,155
I'm a nice person.

565
00:42:24,374 --> 00:42:25,892
What's going on here?

566
00:42:30,697 --> 00:42:32,665
I should've eaten something.

567
00:42:36,803 --> 00:42:40,172
Will someone please
get her a glass of milk?

568
00:42:40,224 --> 00:42:42,058
Don, can I talk to you for a second?

569
00:42:47,480 --> 00:42:49,815
What the hell was that?

570
00:42:49,883 --> 00:42:51,384
Your wife's drunk.

571
00:42:55,422 --> 00:42:57,657
I don't know what I did
to get under your skin.

572
00:42:59,393 --> 00:43:00,793
Roger, it's late.

573
00:43:03,397 --> 00:43:05,181
You know, my mother was right:

574
00:43:05,265 --> 00:43:08,284
It's a mistake to be
conspicuously happy.

575
00:43:08,318 --> 00:43:10,336
Some people don't like it.

576
00:43:11,588 --> 00:43:13,589
No one thinks you're happy.

577
00:43:13,674 --> 00:43:15,975
They think you're foolish.

578
00:43:20,747 --> 00:43:22,415
You know, that's the great
thing about a place like this... 

579
00:43:24,250 --> 00:43:26,252
You can come here and be happy,

580
00:43:26,286 --> 00:43:28,521
and you get to choose your guests.

581
00:43:49,643 --> 00:43:51,844
Good night, Grandpa.

582
00:43:51,895 --> 00:43:52,979
Get in here.

583
00:44:00,954 --> 00:44:02,655
Sit down.

584
00:44:22,476 --> 00:44:24,143
Where were we?

585
00:44:39,225 --> 00:44:41,627
"The rustic manners of a prince

586
00:44:41,662 --> 00:44:43,713
who disdained such glory,

587
00:44:43,797 --> 00:44:47,499
and was insensible of such happiness,

588
00:44:47,551 --> 00:44:50,002
soon disgusted

589
00:44:50,070 --> 00:44:52,521
the delicacy of his subjects;

590
00:44:52,606 --> 00:44:55,691
and the effeminate orientals

591
00:44:55,776 --> 00:44:58,377
could neither imitate nor admire

592
00:44:58,412 --> 00:45:00,579
the severe simplicity..."

593
00:45:00,613 --> 00:45:02,415
"...which Julian always maintained

594
00:45:02,449 --> 00:45:04,133
and sometimes affected."

